&gt;&gt;Shibani: Actually, that, that spot is Corona
Heights. The view may not be exactly like

00:29:19.470 --> 00:29:27.010
that and the fog is not that, it doesn't comply
quite as readily, but yeah, it has that sort

00:29:27.010 --> 00:29:31.740
of a spectacle to it on the right day. It
will just give you that kind of feeling. So,

00:29:31.740 --> 00:29:35.270
but yeah, if you climb up there on the top
of Corona Heights, you can get a pretty spectacular

00:29:35.270 --> 00:29:36.270
view.

00:29:36.270 --> 00:29:44.830
&gt;&gt;Mahim: Great. And so I think a question
is back there in the very back.

00:29:44.830 --> 00:29:48.060
So, the question is why the Bay Area for the
film?

00:29:48.060 --> 00:29:52.460
&gt;&gt;Shibani: So I could get a chance to come
back to San Francisco, which I try to do every

00:29:52.460 --> 00:29:53.460
given opportunity.

00:29:53.460 --> 00:29:54.460
[laughter]

00:29:54.460 --> 00:29:56.809
No, actually, what to me really would appeal
about San Francisco in particular, is the

00:29:56.809 --> 00:30:01.480
fact that Mandira and Rizwan have a, a very
quirky romance. I mean, it's not every day

00:30:01.480 --> 00:30:12.830
that you see, see, sort of a woman having
a romantic relationship with somebody who,

00:30:12.830 --> 00:30:18.669
you know, she's not quite ready for and who's
significantly different. So, their, the flow

00:30:18.669 --> 00:30:24.460
of their romance was had that sort of quirky,
unpredictable quality which I felt the city

00:30:24.460 --> 00:30:32.730
really enhanced because it allows that sort
of "Hey, anything can happen here" sort of

00:30:32.730 --> 00:30:36.740
feel to it. So, I'm, that's why San Francisco,
besides, of course, my love for it.

00:30:36.740 --> 00:30:38.559
&gt;&gt;Mahim: Great. I think there's a question
in the cap.

00:30:38.559 --> 00:30:47.720
So the question is how did you get started
as a writer and do you want to venture into

00:30:47.720 --> 00:30:48.720
Hollywood?

00:30:48.720 --> 00:30:57.899
&gt;&gt;Shibani: I think I was, I was always a writer
in denial. I always loved reading and was

00:30:57.899 --> 00:31:05.010
very good at English composition growing up.
But, I didn't quite maybe have faith in myself

00:31:05.010 --> 00:31:09.070
enough to say, "Wow, can I actually write,
you know?" But, when I was working as a, as

00:31:09.070 --> 00:31:13.929
an executive in, at Sony Television in India,
I was working with a lot of in, my job involved

00:31:13.929 --> 00:31:18.559
working with a lot of writers because it was
part of development, content development.

00:31:18.559 --> 00:31:23.040
And I think that's when I discovered the frustrated
writer in me because I was always expecting

00:31:23.040 --> 00:31:28.600
them to do things the way I wanted, the way
I saw them. You know, and then I said, "Oh,

00:31:28.600 --> 00:31:33.230
that's so not fair because you just want to
write this, right?" I mean, it's not about

00:31:33.230 --> 00:31:37.049
whether what they're doing is really great
or not. So I decided not to do that and not

00:31:37.049 --> 00:31:45.450
be an ogre and started writing myself on weekends
and that's how the first script came about.

00:31:45.450 --> 00:31:52.320
That was, that script never got made so for
anybody who's wanting to write either in the

00:31:52.320 --> 00:31:59.000
audience here or elsewhere, just an attachment
to note, that you always have a great attachment

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:03.580
to the first thing you ever write, but you
should start writing it knowing that nothing

00:32:03.580 --> 00:32:09.370
may ever happen to it; happen off it, you
know? Because, in retrospect, I think it was

00:32:09.370 --> 00:32:13.649
a beauti-, a fantastic beginning. I couldn't
have asked for anything better, but it wasn't

00:32:13.649 --> 00:32:18.291
the first thing I ever wrote. So, that often
happens and you have to sort of go with the

00:32:18.291 --> 00:32:24.590
flow as far as that's concerned. And, I forgot
the second part of your, his question, sorry.

00:32:24.590 --> 00:32:27.460
&gt;&gt;Mahim: Oh, Hollywood, are you interested
in making films for Hollywood?

00:32:27.460 --> 00:32:32.741
&gt;&gt;Shibani: Oh, in Hollywood. Yeah, I'm certainly
interested in, in writing in the English language.

00:32:32.741 --> 00:32:37.940
It is my first language. Now, whether that
would be a Hollywood production per se, or

00:32:37.940 --> 00:32:43.100
just an international production, or an Indie
film, I don't know. I mean, probably the latter,

00:32:43.100 --> 00:32:52.899
you know? But I, because I've lived in the
U.S. for as long as I have, because my thinking

00:32:52.899 --> 00:33:00.330
mind and my, my processes are so geared towards
the English language that, I think that I

00:33:00.330 --> 00:33:04.679
would be remiss if I didn't attempt at least
to express that.

00:33:04.679 --> 00:33:07.640
&gt;&gt;Mahim: Maybe it can be about Google.

00:33:07.640 --> 00:33:09.600
&gt;&gt;Shibani: Maybe it can be about Google.

00:33:09.600 --> 00:33:10.600
[laughter]

00:33:10.600 --> 00:33:12.560
&gt;&gt;Mahim: Great. Yes, you right there.

00:33:12.560 --> 00:33:17.941
So, the first question was since this was
more internationally distributed, did you

00:33:17.941 --> 00:33:22.179
have a different audience in mind when you
wrote it and were creating it? And the second

00:33:22.179 --> 00:33:27.059
question is do you have any more projects
with Karan Johar in the future?

00:33:27.059 --> 00:33:30.919
&gt;&gt;Shibani: Yes, actually, I did have a different
audience in mind, I mean, it was always going

00:33:30.919 --> 00:33:36.269
to be a Hindi film so your core audience is
always going to be people that, that understand

00:33:36.269 --> 00:33:39.070
the language and are familiar with the culture
and with the, with the actors.

00:33:39.070 --> 00:33:46.019
I mean, that is always where you begin. But,
it was certainly, it was certainly something

00:33:46.019 --> 00:33:55.230
that because the scope of the story is so
contemporary and yet so universal, we always

00:33:55.230 --> 00:34:00.370
hoped that it will be something that will
touch people regardless of culture and country,

00:34:00.370 --> 00:34:07.559
and more on a basis of being part of the human
race.

00:34:07.559 --> 00:34:13.760
Fortunately it, it, we've been very successful
in that and have had some wonderful emails

00:34:13.760 --> 00:34:18.131
and, and contacts from people from, from many
different parts of the world, like Egypt and

00:34:18.131 --> 00:34:28.000
Syria and Indonesia and so, and Germany, and
it's just been, it's been really gratifying.

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:34.010
As far as projects in the future, I, Karan
has to only sort of pick up the phone and

00:34:34.010 --> 00:34:40.310
say, "I'm doing, I don't know, a Space Invaders
3," and I'll be like, "Ok, when? When do we

00:34:40.310 --> 00:34:45.520
start?" He's, he's very special to me and
has been greatly instrumental in, in what,

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:50.970
in doing work that I can believe in, so when,
so whenever he decides that it's something

00:34:50.970 --> 00:34:55.879
he wants to do with me, I'm more than happy
to do it.

00:34:55.879 --> 00:34:58.320
&gt;&gt;Mahim: Great. Yes, right there.

00:34:58.320 --> 00:35:04.810
So the question is what was it like filming
in San Francisco? A lot of the scenes in the

00:35:04.810 --> 00:35:08.710
movie have large crowds versus in New York
and India and other places.

00:35:08.710 --> 00:35:14.190
&gt;&gt;Shibani: I don't know about the crowd's
portion of it, but I had a wonderful experience

00:35:14.190 --> 00:35:19.031
shooting in San Francisco because my job was
done; everyone else was working. But, and

00:35:19.031 --> 00:35:22.880
it's always great to be in San Francisco,
but more than that, I think that the people

00:35:22.880 --> 00:35:28.240
and the city were just, are always very welcoming.
I mean, there's a very easy, relaxed sort

00:35:28.240 --> 00:35:33.830
of set up in shooting in San Francisco. Because
there aren't great, huge crowds and lots of

00:35:33.830 --> 00:35:41.070
cars and, so just blocking off a portion or
whatever, is not as much of a task as it can

00:35:41.070 --> 00:35:46.089
be in New York or in Bombay, you know? So,
and then the people are nice. I mean, I don't

00:35:46.089 --> 00:35:50.030
know, it's, it's gotta do with, with that
cold air that comes off the Bay, I suppose.

00:35:50.030 --> 00:35:55.089
I, the people are just nice, so it just made,
it made the process for us very, very smooth

00:35:55.089 --> 00:35:56.690
and just very, very fruitful.

00:35:56.690 --> 00:35:59.930
&gt;&gt;Mahim: I think we have time for two more
questions. So, you in the front.

00:35:59.930 --> 00:36:10.150
So, like most Bollywood films, there are lots
of dance sequences, so why not in this film?

00:36:10.150 --> 00:36:13.520
&gt;&gt;Shibani: God, imagine if Rizwan in the middle
of all of this had to break out into a break-dance,

00:36:13.520 --> 00:36:18.911
my God! How would that be? So, yes, it was
a conscious decision because there was a,

00:36:18.911 --> 00:36:28.150
you know it was important for it, for the
topic that we addressed is, is a, more than

00:36:28.150 --> 00:36:32.610
a serious issue, it's more, it's an emotional
issue and it's a sensitive issue for a lot

00:36:32.610 --> 00:36:33.610
of people.

00:36:33.610 --> 00:36:37.790
So, we didn't want to sort of trivialize it
in any way or create a situation where it

00:36:37.790 --> 00:36:41.780
just becomes unbelievable and laughable in
any way because that was just, that would

00:36:41.780 --> 00:36:46.770
just be terrible. So, so, yes, it was a, it
was a conscious, it was a conscious decision.

00:36:46.770 --> 00:36:51.270
Because the idea really behind this film is
